nd \u2018B\u2019 <br>\nCH<sub>3</sub> - CH = CH - CH<sub>3</sub> $$\\buildrel {{O_3}} \\over\n \\longrightarrow $$ A $$\\mathrel{\\mathop{\\kern0pt\\longrightarrow}\n\\limits_{Zn}^{H{}_2O}} $$ B<br>\nThe compound B is","options":["CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CHO ","CH<sub>3</sub>COCH<sub>3</sub>","CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>COCH<sub>3</sub>","CH<sub>3</sub>CHO"],"correctOption":3,"solution":"Completing the sequence of given reactions, \n<br><br><img class=\"question-image\" src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/fOdpotjlwmMERT8t2/5DAGOWiM7SpxClu55aVvH5fz0m1Tf/WKRwNXqDhlCWP0WB0PDgJW/image.png\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"AIEEE 2008 Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 162 English Explanation\"> \n<br><br>Thus $$'B'\\,\\,$$ is $$\\,\\,C{H_3}CHO$$ \n<br><br>Hence $$(d)$$ is correct answer.","marks":4,"negativeMarks":-1,"topic":"Hydrocarbon","correctOptionsArray":[2,3]},{"id":"TBknNjn1dDvFewtKjzjgy2xukftcekpo","questionNumber":5,"subject":"Chemistry","section":"A","questionType":"MCQ","questionText":"The major product of the following reaction is :\n<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/jgy2xukftcaznj/71b24588-53f9-4210-8a13-90f044d40491/ed0448f0-0547-11eb-8293-3b6cc591631c/file-jgy2xukftcaznk-289w.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2020 (Online) 6th September Morning Slot Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 116 English\">","options":["<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/jgy2xukftcbphg/1fb9a5a5-dd0a-4f1e-a27d-f8ec11a51768/00f87840-0548-11eb-8293-3b6cc591631c/file-jgy2xukftcbphh-212w.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2020 (Online) 6th September Morning Slot Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 116 English Option 1\">","<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/jgy2xukftcca4h/bc60106f-ff47-4c27-9cbb-527c402de308/10ea0b10-0548-11eb-8293-3b6cc591631c/file-jgy2xukftcca4i-223w.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2020 (Online) 6th September Morning Slot Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 116 English Option 2\">","<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/jgy2xukftccvxa/b71a1d6a-667b-4c12-9e7a-26ba73be8c10/21c11be0-0548-11eb-8293-3b6cc591631c/file-jgy2xukftccvxb-205w.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2020 (Online) 6th September Morning Slot Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 116 English Option 3\">","<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/jgy2xukftcdn6n/875108a3-69e9-4314-a168-0a6d900f3a3f/36cfe2f0-0548-11eb-8293-3b6cc591631c/file-jgy2xukftcdn6o-173w.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2020 (Online) 6th September Morning Slot Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 116 English Option 4\">"],"correctOption":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/jgy2xukgt4pv2x/ebb77573-e0a6-432d-abf1-a4f3dd2f4f91/78f7a890-18f6-11eb-8293-3b6cc591631c/file-jgy2xukgt4pv2y-493w.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2020 (Online) 6th September Morning Slot Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 116 English Explanation\">","marks":4,"negativeMarks":-1,"topic":"Hydrocarbon"},{"id":"1l2sqgk7a","questionNumber":6,"subject":"Chemistry","section":"A","questionType":"MCQ","questionText":"<p>The maximum number of isomers (including stereoisomers) that are possible on mono-chlorination of the following compound, is ____________.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dheywx/2ec5a646-a273-46b4-893b-e06a21375c16/b38db600-6507-11ef-8452-815a3bbe3903/file-jaoe38c1m0dheyxs.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dheywx/2ec5a646-a273-46b4-893b-e06a21375c16/b38db600-6507-11ef-8452-815a3bbe3903/file-jaoe38c1m0dheyxs.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English\"></p>","options":[],"correctOption":0,"solution":"<p>(i) The monochlorination products obtained depends upon the kinds of hydrogen present in the molecule.</p>\n<p>(ii) There are four different types of hydrogen in the molecule; $\\mathrm{H}_a, \\mathrm{H}_b, \\mathrm{H}_c$ and $\\mathrm{H}_d$.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsn44q/ef9cd3b2-39b5-4ed4-bc4e-563a9e0fa0d5/9a75e5d0-6533-11ef-8476-99023ad6136d/file-jaoe38c1m0dsn44t.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsn44q/ef9cd3b2-39b5-4ed4-bc4e-563a9e0fa0d5/9a75e5d0-6533-11ef-8476-99023ad6136d/file-jaoe38c1m0dsn44t.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>(iii) The monochlorination products obtained on replacement of these hydrogen are as follows :</p>\n<p>(a) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}_a$ with chlorine :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsqq3e/c3c25250-178a-49f6-8e8e-9d4aaef43aa0/fed9f890-6533-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsqq3f.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsqq3e/c3c25250-178a-49f6-8e8e-9d4aaef43aa0/fed9f890-6533-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsqq3f.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 2\"></p>\n<p>Since, the carbon is a chiral; only one monochlorination isomer is possible when $\\mathrm{H}_a$ is replaced by chlorine.</p>\n<p>(b) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}_b$ with chlorine :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsuc49/ffc22ff5-0bf4-410c-9f12-4e23a16d388e/634adc90-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsuc4a.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsuc49/ffc22ff5-0bf4-410c-9f12-4e23a16d388e/634adc90-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsuc4a.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 3\"></p>\n<p>Since all the carbons are a chiral; only one monochlorination product is possible by when $\\mathrm{H}_b$ replaced by Cl .</p>\n<p>(c) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}_c$ with chlorine</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dsw3u2/a0c5bbac-7d88-48ea-8023-ee28147e2ee9/94831ca0-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsw3u3.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dsw3u2/a0c5bbac-7d88-48ea-8023-ee28147e2ee9/94831ca0-6534-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dsw3u3.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 4\"></p>\n<p>The carbon on which hydrogen is replaced by chlorine becomes chiral; hence R/S isomers exist.</p>\n<p>Also, carbon adjacent to the carbon on which hydrogen $\\left(\\mathrm{H}_c\\right)$ is replaced, is also chiral; hence, it will also exist as a pair of enantiomer $R / S$ four monochlorination products (which are stereoisomers or optical isomers) are possible.\n\n<br><br>(d) Replacing $\\mathrm{H}^d$ by chlorine :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m0dt07zc/d3bb8d48-6d1a-4342-b6c9-db2fc6a49452/06f3d590-6535-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dt07zd.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m0dt07zc/d3bb8d48-6d1a-4342-b6c9-db2fc6a49452/06f3d590-6535-11ef-8337-277ca37013fe/file-jaoe38c1m0dt07zd.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"IIT-JEE 2011 Paper 2 Offline Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 14 English Explanation 5\"></p>\n<p>The central carbon $\\left({ }^*\\right)$ becomes chiral when $\\mathrm{H}^d$ is replaced by chlorine; hence $R / S$ isomers exist. Two monochlorination products are possible (stereoisomers or optical isomers) are possible. \n<br><br>Total number of isomers possible are 8.</p>","marks":3,"negativeMarks":-1,"topic":"Hydrocarbon"},{"id":"1lh31xzr0","questionNumber":7,"subject":"Chemistry","section":"A","questionType":"MCQ","questionText":"<p>Find out the major product from the following reaction.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lh5ool78/816a3c98-fc3a-49de-a980-aa52acde34b2/bd8b0850-e895-11ed-8179-292e62481b94/file-1lh5ool79.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lh5ool78/816a3c98-fc3a-49de-a980-aa52acde34b2/bd8b0850-e895-11ed-8179-292e62481b94/file-1lh5ool79.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh\" alt=\"JEE Main 2023 (Online) 6th April Evening Shift Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 60 English\"></p>","options":["<img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lh5op0k6/58a5cb71-c6f6-4690-aa80-a3993c7f79e9/c9684b60-e895-11ed-8179-292e62481b94/file-1lh5op0k7.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lh5op0k6/58a5cb71-c6f6-4690-aa80-a3993c7f79e9/c9684b60-e895-11ed-8179-292e62481b94/file-1lh5op0k7.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh\" alt=\"JEE Main 2023 (Online) 6th April Evening Shift Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Qu